1
00:01:55,115 --> 00:01:56,719
Railen.

2
00:02:01,187 --> 00:02:03,030
I'm on my way.

3
00:02:14,300 --> 00:02:15,870
Gentlemen.

4
00:02:16,236 --> 00:02:18,837
All right. Tell me what we know.

5
00:02:18,838 --> 00:02:20,339
Intel confirms that this morning,

6
00:02:20,340 --> 00:02:24,676
5:15 A.M. Eastern Standard Time,
12:45 P.M. in Iran,

7
00:02:24,677 --> 00:02:28,280
the Iranian government test detonated
a small nuclear device.

8
00:02:28,281 --> 00:02:30,716
It was set off in an underground cavern
in a remote area,

9
00:02:30,717 --> 00:02:33,685
350 kilometers southeast of Tehran.

10
00:02:33,686 --> 00:02:36,221
The bang was a little bigger
than they were expecting.

11
00:02:36,222 --> 00:02:40,192
Mm. So much for their
non-military nuclear agenda.

12
00:02:40,293 --> 00:02:41,727
No coffee this morning?

13
00:02:41,728 --> 00:02:43,695
Only the President gets coffee in here.

14
00:02:43,696 --> 00:02:44,630
Right.

15
00:02:44,631 --> 00:02:47,032
Well, he's going to need something
a little bit stronger than coffee

16
00:02:47,033 --> 00:02:48,367
when he gets back.

17
00:02:48,368 --> 00:02:49,535
If we'd had some proof earlier,

18
00:02:49,536 --> 00:02:51,470
we could have taken out
their reactor site

19
00:02:51,471 --> 00:02:53,071
when we had the chance.

20
00:02:53,072 --> 00:02:55,207
The reactor wasn't the source.

21
00:02:55,208 --> 00:02:57,809
Previous intel put the Iranians'
Weapons Program a good year

22
00:02:57,810 --> 00:03:01,079
and a half away from being able to
produce a viable device.

23
00:03:01,080 --> 00:03:03,882
We've since learned that
they may have acquired nuclear materials

24
00:03:03,883 --> 00:03:06,418
through the black market in Pakistan.

25
00:03:06,419 --> 00:03:08,720
You said materials plural.

26
00:03:08,721 --> 00:03:11,990
Are you trying to tell me
that they may have more than one nuke?

27
00:03:11,991 --> 00:03:13,659
The Taliban claims to have seized

28
00:03:13,660 --> 00:03:16,495
a cache of 3 devices in Pakistan
a month ago.

29
00:03:16,496 --> 00:03:19,665
It's likely they sold them to Iran
right under our nose.

30
00:03:19,666 --> 00:03:21,804
And you're telling me now?

31
00:03:21,834 --> 00:03:24,169
The President wanted
intel confirmation before

32
00:03:24,170 --> 00:03:26,538
Well, I'd say we got that today.

33
00:03:26,539 --> 00:03:29,441
Except now,
a tactical strike is too risky.

34
00:03:29,442 --> 00:03:30,842
We bomb the wrong place,

35
00:03:30,843 --> 00:03:33,445
we'll put a mushroom cloud
over the Middle East.

36
00:03:33,446 --> 00:03:36,449
Not the best foreign policy strategy.

37
00:03:36,516 --> 00:03:40,085
All right.
The President is in Tokyo.

38
00:03:40,086 --> 00:03:42,854
I'll get Chief of Staff Jenkins
to brief him,

39
00:03:42,855 --> 00:03:45,190
and get him back to D.C.
before tomorrow morning.

40
00:03:45,191 --> 00:03:49,728
In the meantime, let's get
Homeland Security and DOD in the loop.

41
00:03:49,729 --> 00:03:51,563
Director Thompson will update intel

42
00:03:51,564 --> 00:03:54,666
and we'll meet back here
this afternoon 16:00

43
00:03:54,667 --> 00:03:56,168
Let's go.

44
00:04:19,759 --> 00:04:21,960
Worms, dear boy.

45
00:04:21,961 --> 00:04:26,398
If you expect to lure anything
from this godforsaken mud puddle,

46
00:04:26,399 --> 00:04:30,035
you must use that
which comes from the Earth, worms.

47
00:04:30,036 --> 00:04:32,471
You're absolutely right, Dad.

48
00:04:32,472 --> 00:04:34,849
Yeah, of course I'm right,
I'm your father.

49
00:04:36,943 --> 00:04:39,252
It's quite nice here, actually.

50
00:04:40,980 --> 00:04:43,016
Your mother would have loved it.

51
00:04:43,416 --> 00:04:45,862
Yeah.

52
00:04:49,822 --> 00:04:51,823
You don't really expect to
catch anything with that, will you?

53
00:04:51,824 --> 00:04:54,226
I've got some worms in the truck
if you like.

54
00:04:54,227 --> 00:04:55,294
No, no, no, no, no, no.

55
00:04:55,295 --> 00:04:56,461
That's all right.

56
00:04:56,462 --> 00:05:00,569
I'm just, just here
for the scenery anyway.

57
00:05:01,868 --> 00:05:03,302
Oh, don't worry.

58
00:05:03,303 --> 00:05:05,337
Got breakfast already on the stove.

59
00:05:05,338 --> 00:05:06,571
Oh, good.

60
00:05:06,572 --> 00:05:07,973
Well.

61
00:05:07,974 --> 00:05:10,442
I was half expecting to
have to clean a fish

62
00:05:10,443 --> 00:05:12,911
before you gave me something
to eat out here.

63
00:05:12,912 --> 00:05:15,085
I thought you liked this place.

64
00:05:15,148 --> 00:05:17,382
I said your mother would have liked it.

65
00:05:17,383 --> 00:05:18,550
Oh.

66
00:05:18,551 --> 00:05:21,753
I would have preferred you bought a house
in Beverly Hills.

67
00:05:21,754 --> 00:05:24,556
Taken me to see some celebrities
and walk the red carpet.

68
00:05:24,557 --> 00:05:27,826
Come on, Dad,
I'm not that kind of famous.

69
00:05:27,827 --> 00:05:29,127
Just wrote a book.

70
00:05:29,128 --> 00:05:31,301
A best seller.

71
00:05:31,864 --> 00:05:33,031
The public loved it.

72
00:05:33,032 --> 00:05:36,376
Yeah, those at the science
fiction conventions.

73
00:05:36,536 --> 00:05:39,237
My peers didn't seem to
think much of it,

74
00:05:39,238 --> 00:05:42,275
if they even read it at all, that is.

75
00:05:42,742 --> 00:05:45,119
Eggheads. Every one of them.

76
00:05:46,879 --> 00:05:49,086
Uh, no offense.

77
00:05:50,283 --> 00:05:54,519
You are going to regret it out here
when the first snow storm strikes.

78
00:05:54,520 --> 00:05:57,432
Unless you've made plans to fly south
for the winter.

79
00:06:03,029 --> 00:06:06,271
Of course,
flying east is interesting too.

80
00:06:06,566 --> 00:06:08,545
Ah, silly birds.

81
00:06:10,169 --> 00:06:12,080
Do you think they're lost?

82
00:06:20,913 --> 00:06:22,858
Come on, let's go.

83
00:06:28,688 --> 00:06:30,132
Melanie?

84
00:06:34,026 --> 00:06:35,560
Uh, Rose Cancer Clinic?

85
00:06:35,561 --> 00:06:37,095
Knock it off!

86
00:06:37,096 --> 00:06:40,167
Where am I supposed to go?
Jeez, Louise.

87
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:41,944
Hi.

88
00:06:42,068 --> 00:06:44,548
Dr. Jenna Ward, I presume.

89
00:06:44,604 --> 00:06:46,872
I know, I'm late.
I'm late, Joe, I know.

90
00:06:46,873 --> 00:06:50,642
It's an accident or something.
We're all just sitting here.

91
00:06:50,643 --> 00:06:53,054
Really? I didn't even notice.

92
00:06:53,346 --> 00:06:55,013
I got 2 patients in the waiting room,
1 in back,

93
00:06:55,014 --> 00:06:57,149
and Melanie's disappeared
to get coffee again.

94
00:06:57,150 --> 00:06:59,684
We really need to get a coffee maker
for the office.

95
00:06:59,685 --> 00:07:01,420
Nah. It wouldn't change anything.

96
00:07:01,421 --> 00:07:04,089
Then someone would just have to
teach her how to brew coffee.

97
00:07:04,090 --> 00:07:06,425
And, you know, hot water confuses her.

98
00:07:06,426 --> 00:07:09,294
Well, don't blame me, I didn't hire her.

99
00:07:09,295 --> 00:07:12,063
Well, I guess I wasn't looking at
her resume during the interview.

100
00:07:12,064 --> 00:07:13,508
Pig.

101
00:07:13,566 --> 00:07:15,739
Knock it off!

102
00:07:15,835 --> 00:07:17,135
Not you, Joe. Sorry.

103
00:07:17,136 --> 00:07:18,670
Anything pressing?

104
00:07:18,671 --> 00:07:21,440
Yeah, yeah.
Actually we got another patient

105
00:07:21,441 --> 00:07:23,909
reporting fatigue, dizziness,
and nausea.

106
00:07:23,910 --> 00:07:25,911
The same symptoms
as the ones from yesterday.

107
00:07:25,912 --> 00:07:27,345
Chemo reaction?

108
00:07:27,346 --> 00:07:30,882
No, no. She finished
her chemo radiation therapy months ago.

109
00:07:30,883 --> 00:07:32,918
Completely successful,
she'd been in remission ever since then.

110
00:07:32,919 --> 00:07:34,693
This is more like,

111
00:07:35,655 --> 00:07:38,623
well, altitude sickness.

112
00:07:38,624 --> 00:07:40,725
We're like, 5 miles from the ocean.

113
00:07:40,726 --> 00:07:42,627
How could it be altitude sickness?

114
00:07:42,628 --> 00:07:44,664
Well, beats me.

115
00:07:44,864 --> 00:07:46,531
Oh, and your buddy Alberto is back.

116
00:07:46,532 --> 00:07:50,912
Said that he, uh, he's having
his memory erased by someone named Guy.

117
00:07:51,437 --> 00:07:53,972
Don't you just love your job,
Dr. Bradford?

118
00:07:53,973 --> 00:07:55,340
Oh yeah.

119
00:07:55,341 --> 00:07:57,476
Oh, and your brother, Marty called,
he had to cancel dinner tonight

120
00:07:57,477 --> 00:07:59,744
because, uh, something came up at work.

121
00:07:59,745 --> 00:08:01,880
And I was gonna cook too.

122
00:08:01,881 --> 00:08:04,588
Oh, that's perfect. I was gonna eat.

123
00:08:05,218 --> 00:08:08,053
Come on. I know you really
wanted to invite me instead.

124
00:08:08,054 --> 00:08:09,828
Dream on.

125
00:08:10,223 --> 00:08:11,289
Whoa!

126
00:08:11,290 --> 00:08:12,724
Stop it!

127
00:08:12,725 --> 00:08:14,499
Screw you!

128
00:08:26,472 --> 00:08:28,573
Dr. Ward.
-What's up, Kimi?

129
00:08:28,574 --> 00:08:30,242
Levels of solar radiation.

130
00:08:30,243 --> 00:08:33,011
Just since last night,
there's been a 40 rem spike.

131
00:08:33,012 --> 00:08:35,046
Did you monitor for solar flares?

132
00:08:35,047 --> 00:08:36,414
Yeah, and that's not it.

133
00:08:36,415 --> 00:08:38,717
There's no unusual solar activity at all.

134
00:08:38,718 --> 00:08:40,418
Gamma in the thermosphere is unchanged.

135
00:08:40,419 --> 00:08:42,988
We're just getting more of it
down here on the surface.

136
00:08:42,989 --> 00:08:45,690
Well, that doesn't make any sense.

137
00:08:45,691 --> 00:08:48,034
Uh, show me the numbers, Ethan.

138
00:08:50,263 --> 00:08:51,696
I double checked the numbers.

139
00:08:51,697 --> 00:08:53,899
I shot them over to the WDC
for confirmation.

140
00:08:53,900 --> 00:08:54,566
What did they say?

141
00:08:54,567 --> 00:08:57,069
They said they'd get back to us.

142
00:08:57,537 --> 00:09:00,872
Sorry I had to bring you in, Dr. Ward.
I know you had plans.

143
00:09:00,873 --> 00:09:03,580
Oh, no. That's okay.

144
00:09:03,776 --> 00:09:07,018
My sister was cooking,
so, you actually did me a favor.

145
00:09:12,084 --> 00:09:14,154
This can't be good.

146
00:09:19,458 --> 00:09:21,059
This is an internal problem.

147
00:09:21,060 --> 00:09:22,360
It's not coming from the sun.

148
00:09:22,361 --> 00:09:24,229
Right. The solar wind hasn't changed.

149
00:09:24,230 --> 00:09:26,331
The Earth's rotation has.

150
00:09:26,332 --> 00:09:29,335
From these readings, it looks like

151
00:09:29,869 --> 00:09:31,848
we're slowing down.

152
00:09:33,639 --> 00:09:35,840
Pull up all 200 NOAA observatories.

153
00:09:35,841 --> 00:09:38,009
Plug the raw data into a model.

154
00:09:38,010 --> 00:09:39,344
Let's, uh, focus.

155
00:09:39,345 --> 00:09:41,483
See if we can figure this thing out.

156
00:09:57,363 --> 00:09:59,308
Something's not right.

157
00:10:49,815 --> 00:10:51,916
Ah, you look nice.

158
00:10:51,917 --> 00:10:53,251
Where are you off to?

159
00:10:53,252 --> 00:10:56,494
Ah, I'm just meeting an acquaintance
for dinner.

160
00:10:56,589 --> 00:10:58,295
Ah-ha.

161
00:11:17,977 --> 00:11:20,045
Oh, I hope you don't mind my decorating.

162
00:11:20,046 --> 00:11:22,113
I made a few frames.
It was a little project of mine.

163
00:11:22,114 --> 00:11:23,448
I was going to put them up.

164
00:11:23,449 --> 00:11:24,949
No, no, that's fine.

165
00:11:24,950 --> 00:11:26,217
They're good pictures.

166
00:11:26,218 --> 00:11:28,186
I particularly like the one
of you and Mom.

167
00:11:28,187 --> 00:11:30,555
Ah, yes. That was a fine day.

168
00:11:30,556 --> 00:11:32,857
And a fancy restaurant you took us to.

169
00:11:32,858 --> 00:11:35,269
Yeah, she was happy.

170
00:11:35,528 --> 00:11:37,029
Yeah.

171
00:11:37,930 --> 00:11:40,999
If only I'd known
how little time we had left.

172
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:42,867
No one knew, Dad.

173
00:11:42,868 --> 00:11:44,936
But like you said, she was happy.

174
00:11:44,937 --> 00:11:46,438
And you can't ask for more than that.

175
00:11:46,439 --> 00:11:48,039
Yes.

176
00:11:48,040 --> 00:11:51,609
Well, it is 50 miles to town.

177
00:11:51,610 --> 00:11:55,280
I, I think I'll stay in this evening.

178
00:11:55,281 --> 00:11:58,616
Come on, Dad, it's been 7 years.

179
00:11:58,617 --> 00:12:01,654
Mom wouldn't want you to
spend the rest of your life alone.

180
00:12:04,757 --> 00:12:06,257
What about you?

181
00:12:06,258 --> 00:12:08,499
Well, I'm not alone, am I?

182
00:12:08,794 --> 00:12:10,739
You're always here.

183
00:12:11,297 --> 00:12:12,864
Well, you know what I mean.

184
00:12:12,865 --> 00:12:15,641
You were happy once too, with Jenna.

185
00:12:17,002 --> 00:12:18,845
Thanks, Dad.

186
00:12:19,305 --> 00:12:20,205
Thanks for caring.

187
00:12:20,206 --> 00:12:22,707
I, I really do appreciate it.

188
00:12:22,708 --> 00:12:25,449
This isn't about caring.

189
00:12:25,778 --> 00:12:28,451
But I do know happiness.

190
00:12:29,115 --> 00:12:31,788
And we're all entitled to that.

191
00:12:32,885 --> 00:12:34,420
I'm fine.

192
00:12:34,587 --> 00:12:35,920
Good.

193
00:12:35,921 --> 00:12:37,589
Then why don't you come along with me?

194
00:12:38,424 --> 00:12:41,092
I'm sure you're worried
I'll drive into a ditch or something.

195
00:12:41,093 --> 00:12:43,428
No, that's okay. You, you go ahead.

196
00:12:43,429 --> 00:12:45,931
I, I've got everything I need.

197
00:12:49,135 --> 00:12:51,114
Not everything, my boy.

198
00:12:52,738 --> 00:12:54,372
You gonna bring her some flowers?

199
00:12:54,373 --> 00:12:56,074
Of course.

200
00:12:56,075 --> 00:12:58,646
We can't all be naturally charming.

201
00:12:59,378 --> 00:13:01,516
Some of us need props.

202
00:13:14,827 --> 00:13:16,829
Tallyho!

203
00:13:43,756 --> 00:13:45,428
It's happening.

204
00:13:55,601 --> 00:13:57,603
What are you doing now?

205
00:14:12,952 --> 00:14:14,897
What the hell is going on?

206
00:14:16,889 --> 00:14:18,732
It was a warning.

207
00:14:19,391 --> 00:14:20,959
She is not finished yet.

208
00:14:20,960 --> 00:14:22,962
Hey, Al, you still here?

209
00:14:23,495 --> 00:14:25,269
Who are you?

210
00:14:25,764 --> 00:14:28,335
Well, Alberto, it's, it's me.

211
00:14:28,400 --> 00:14:30,072
Dr. Bradford.

212
00:14:30,236 --> 00:14:32,272
I mean, I saw you this morning.

213
00:14:32,638 --> 00:14:34,845
Did you feel it, Doctor?

214
00:14:34,907 --> 00:14:36,307
The little tremor?
-Yeah.

215
00:14:36,308 --> 00:14:37,575
Yeah. It's nothing
to be worried about, Al.

216
00:14:37,576 --> 00:14:39,277
It's California. That happens.

217
00:14:39,278 --> 00:14:41,280
It's nothing to panic over.

218
00:14:41,280 --> 00:14:43,581
Power outage is a bigger pain
in the neck.

219
00:14:43,582 --> 00:14:45,950
I mean, are you okay?
You want to come down from there?

220
00:14:45,951 --> 00:14:48,488
Something new is happening.

221
00:14:49,655 --> 00:14:51,155
And it's starting now.

222
00:14:51,156 --> 00:14:52,523
Listen, Al.

223
00:14:52,524 --> 00:14:54,292
You're gonna need
a new course of treatment.

224
00:14:54,293 --> 00:14:56,127
Now we can do the follow-up test
and regimen here at the clinic,

225
00:14:56,128 --> 00:14:58,296
but you can't just,
you know, hang out here.

226
00:14:58,297 --> 00:15:00,504
I am waiting for the bus.

227
00:15:02,501 --> 00:15:04,947
My daughter left on the bus.

228
00:15:05,170 --> 00:15:07,445
She said I should stay here.

229
00:15:08,641 --> 00:15:09,908
Well, listen, if you need help. . .

230
00:15:09,909 --> 00:15:13,185
No, no. I am fine.

231
00:15:14,246 --> 00:15:16,014
There is a reason for everything.

232
00:15:16,015 --> 00:15:18,149
It is all connected.

233
00:15:18,150 --> 00:15:20,323
But you can't see it.

234
00:15:21,954 --> 00:15:23,855
You have to feel it.

235
00:15:23,856 --> 00:15:25,256
Okay. Whatever.

236
00:15:25,257 --> 00:15:26,291
I'll make a call.

237
00:15:26,292 --> 00:15:28,493
I know a place you can go
that- that can help.

238
00:15:28,494 --> 00:15:30,028
I ain't going anywhere.

239
00:15:30,029 --> 00:15:33,631
Melanie, uh,
you can't take a 2 hour lunch.

240
00:15:33,632 --> 00:15:35,236
Hi.

241
00:15:37,636 --> 00:15:39,444
You see, Doctor.

242
00:15:40,306 --> 00:15:43,013
You are the one who needs help.

243
00:16:12,838 --> 00:16:15,073
Okay, the doctor will be with you soon.

244
00:16:15,074 --> 00:16:16,746
Gracias.

245
00:16:17,810 --> 00:16:19,220
Ah.

246
00:16:19,812 --> 00:16:22,280
Joe, would you just ask her out already?

247
00:16:22,281 --> 00:16:24,148
Well, I would, but I can't.
I'm her employer.

248
00:16:24,149 --> 00:16:27,721
Exactly. Do us all a favor and fire her.

249
00:16:28,587 --> 00:16:30,566
Yes. Thank you.

250
00:16:31,590 --> 00:16:32,857
Yeah, but do you think
she'd actually go out with me

251
00:16:32,858 --> 00:16:35,497
if I. . . if I fired her?

252
00:16:35,694 --> 00:16:38,196
You know, the city was supposed
to change out these transformers

253
00:16:38,197 --> 00:16:40,231
the last time this happened.

254
00:16:40,232 --> 00:16:41,532
Hey, you know,
maybe we should double date.

255
00:16:41,533 --> 00:16:42,800
You know, less pressure.

256
00:16:42,801 --> 00:16:44,939
Mm, no. I don't think so.

257
00:16:45,604 --> 00:16:47,038
Yeah, but weren't you dating
some scientist guy,

258
00:16:47,039 --> 00:16:48,172
a friend of your brother's?

259
00:16:48,173 --> 00:16:50,341
I was dating him.

260
00:16:50,342 --> 00:16:54,085
Joe. He dumped me. Remember?

261
00:16:54,747 --> 00:16:56,521
Yeah, but,

262
00:16:56,582 --> 00:16:58,254
Jenna, I. . .

263
00:17:01,020 --> 00:17:02,931
I guess that's a no.

264
00:17:22,007 --> 00:17:23,875
The surge knocked out
almost 1/3 of the city

265
00:17:23,876 --> 00:17:25,576
on the old power grid.

266
00:17:25,577 --> 00:17:28,216
The new portions held up, though.

267
00:17:28,747 --> 00:17:31,382
Ethan, what do you got for me?

268
00:17:31,383 --> 00:17:34,485
Um, Cal Tech recorded the tremor
as a 2-point-oh.

269
00:17:34,486 --> 00:17:35,586
Barely even felt it.

270
00:17:35,587 --> 00:17:37,755
Just a, a minor Earth adjustment.

271
00:17:37,756 --> 00:17:38,756
They don't know that.

272
00:17:38,757 --> 00:17:41,559
Uh, well, no. I guess.

273
00:17:41,560 --> 00:17:42,960
No guessing, Ethan.

274
00:17:42,961 --> 00:17:45,963
Not here.
Science is about gathering facts.

275
00:17:45,964 --> 00:17:48,740
Uh, okay.

276
00:17:51,970 --> 00:17:55,383
Are you all right, Dr. Ward?

277
00:18:01,780 --> 00:18:03,759
Yeah, it's just. . .

278
00:18:06,218 --> 00:18:10,256
I- I look at things a certain way
based on what I know to be true.

279
00:18:11,056 --> 00:18:12,657
I can't make the leap
from fact to theory.

280
00:18:12,658 --> 00:18:14,967
I just don't work that way.

281
00:18:15,327 --> 00:18:17,395
Yeah, me neither.

282
00:18:17,396 --> 00:18:18,963
Really?

283
00:18:18,964 --> 00:18:20,531
Well, in most things.

284
00:18:20,532 --> 00:18:22,033
Except for dating.

285
00:18:22,034 --> 00:18:23,569
What?

286
00:18:23,836 --> 00:18:27,572
Well, facts only go so far
when you're dealing with people.

287
00:18:27,573 --> 00:18:32,544
Sometimes it's all about
a leap of faith.

288
00:18:49,328 --> 00:18:51,603
Just stick to the facts.

289
00:18:57,936 --> 00:19:00,171
The Iranian government
is denying reports

290
00:19:00,172 --> 00:19:02,373
that there was any sort of weapons test.

291
00:19:02,374 --> 00:19:04,342
But as you can see
from the satellite surveillance,

292
00:19:04,343 --> 00:19:08,045
this village near Tabas
was leveled by the shockwave.

293
00:19:08,046 --> 00:19:11,215
Now we believe most of the radiation
was contained underground,

294
00:19:11,216 --> 00:19:14,819
but elevated levels are being reported
by neighboring countries.

295
00:19:14,820 --> 00:19:16,387
6 months ago,

296
00:19:16,388 --> 00:19:18,589
a bombing run targeting
their nuclear facilities

297
00:19:18,590 --> 00:19:20,291
was on the table.

298
00:19:20,292 --> 00:19:23,794
You, General Railen, advised restraint.

299
00:19:23,795 --> 00:19:26,197
I advised the President
that without proof

300
00:19:26,198 --> 00:19:29,333
that their enrichment program
was weapons related,

301
00:19:29,334 --> 00:19:33,437
an attack would be a breach
of international law.

302
00:19:33,438 --> 00:19:36,073
Well, then he should've given you
the proof you needed.

303
00:19:36,074 --> 00:19:37,975
All due respect, Mr. McNeil,

304
00:19:37,976 --> 00:19:39,677
you're the Secretary of Defense.

305
00:19:39,678 --> 00:19:41,412
You advised him too.

306
00:19:41,413 --> 00:19:43,080
The only advice I gave him

307
00:19:43,081 --> 00:19:45,082
was to cut out
all the bleeding heart pacifists

308
00:19:45,083 --> 00:19:46,684
from his administration.

309
00:19:46,685 --> 00:19:50,223
Perhaps you lack a little objectivity
in the matter.

310
00:19:50,389 --> 00:19:55,059
No one here is suggesting that
we roll over for the Iranians, McNeil.

311
00:19:55,060 --> 00:19:56,827
But if they're sitting on another nuke,

312
00:19:56,828 --> 00:20:00,631
we have to factor that
into our available response options.

313
00:20:00,632 --> 00:20:02,304
Fine.

314
00:20:02,701 --> 00:20:05,436
Work out a full series
of recommendations.

315
00:20:05,437 --> 00:20:08,679
I'll brief the President
when he returns in the morning.

316
00:20:09,241 --> 00:20:13,778
I want multiple projections
for military engagements.

317
00:20:13,779 --> 00:20:18,694
Consider both conventional
and nuclear options.

318
00:20:25,057 --> 00:20:27,559
Okay, let's get to work.

319
00:20:36,935 --> 00:20:38,336
What is it?

320
00:20:38,337 --> 00:20:41,772
The World Data Center got a call
from some NGDC scientist

321
00:20:41,773 --> 00:20:45,476
who said they've recorded a spike
in radiation levels worldwide.

322
00:20:45,477 --> 00:20:47,422
It can't be connected.

323
00:20:47,579 --> 00:20:48,813
Even under strong wind conditions,

324
00:20:48,814 --> 00:20:51,749
the radiation and the fallout
would be relatively localized.

325
00:20:51,750 --> 00:20:54,085
Yeah, but the center confirmed it.

326
00:20:54,086 --> 00:20:55,353
They say it's everywhere.

327
00:20:55,354 --> 00:20:58,389
Oh, hell. Who's the scientist?

328
00:20:58,390 --> 00:21:01,359
A, um, Martin Ward
from the Los Angeles office.

329
00:21:01,360 --> 00:21:02,860
We can have him send us the data.

330
00:21:02,861 --> 00:21:04,996
No. No. We need to control the source,

331
00:21:04,997 --> 00:21:06,864
keep this contained.

332
00:21:06,865 --> 00:21:09,400
I'll have my office muzzle the WDC.

333
00:21:09,401 --> 00:21:12,279
And then you and I
are going on a quick trip.

334
00:21:17,776 --> 00:21:19,810
So other than the dizziness
and the fatigue,

335
00:21:19,811 --> 00:21:22,791
is there anything else
that's bothering you?

336
00:21:29,154 --> 00:21:30,321
Thank you.

337
00:21:30,322 --> 00:21:33,268
I will take that as a yes.

338
00:21:37,929 --> 00:21:39,297
Okay, now you just rest.

339
00:21:39,298 --> 00:21:40,865
Uh, give this a couple minutes to work.

340
00:21:40,866 --> 00:21:43,142
Okay?

341
00:21:48,807 --> 00:21:49,807
Same symptoms?

342
00:21:49,808 --> 00:21:52,576
Worse. And she finished treatment
2 months ago.

343
00:21:52,577 --> 00:21:54,612
So it's not from the chemo.

344
00:21:54,613 --> 00:21:56,213
She's disoriented and dizzy.

345
00:21:56,214 --> 00:21:58,182
She doesn't seem to know where she is.

346
00:21:58,183 --> 00:22:01,254
I've got 4 more just like her
in reception. Come on.

347
00:22:08,026 --> 00:22:09,760
Okay, this is just very weird.

348
00:22:09,761 --> 00:22:13,331
And it's presenting like, um,
altitude sickness almost, right?

349
00:22:13,332 --> 00:22:16,403
Which doesn't make any sense.
-No. It doesn't.

350
00:22:17,369 --> 00:22:19,712
One second. Mr. Simon?

351
00:22:28,380 --> 00:22:30,655
How are you feeling, Mr. Simon?

352
00:22:32,184 --> 00:22:33,754
Mr. Simon?

353
00:22:38,290 --> 00:22:40,292
Do you know where you are?

354
00:22:46,498 --> 00:22:47,942
Joe.

355
00:22:47,999 --> 00:22:49,300
He is a survivor.

356
00:22:49,301 --> 00:22:50,868
He had his chemo in January.

357
00:22:50,869 --> 00:22:54,905
He did so well with it
that he was mobile within a month.

358
00:22:54,906 --> 00:22:56,741
I just, I don't get it.

359
00:22:56,742 --> 00:22:59,810
We're gonna have to pull
everybody's charts from the last year.

360
00:22:59,811 --> 00:23:01,679
I'll give Debbie at the
Center for Disease Control a call.

361
00:23:01,680 --> 00:23:04,592
Maybe we're dealing with
some kind of localized contagion.

362
00:23:04,750 --> 00:23:06,422
How are you feeling?

363
00:23:06,585 --> 00:23:08,393
I'm fine. You?

364
00:23:08,553 --> 00:23:10,555
Nothing fazes this guy.

365
00:23:14,493 --> 00:23:16,227
She had to go away.

366
00:23:16,228 --> 00:23:18,229
For the baby. You understand?

367
00:23:18,230 --> 00:23:19,597
It's not that she didn't love me.

368
00:23:19,598 --> 00:23:22,666
Uh, uh, it's just that
sometimes we gotta leave.

369
00:23:22,667 --> 00:23:25,269
Uh, Mexico is a good place for her.

370
00:23:25,270 --> 00:23:27,147
How you doing, Al?

371
00:23:28,106 --> 00:23:30,174
Ah, Dr. Jenna.

372
00:23:30,175 --> 00:23:32,052
I know you.

373
00:23:32,544 --> 00:23:36,914
Are you okay? Dr. Joe said that
some guy was stealing your memory?

374
00:23:36,915 --> 00:23:38,349
Not some guy.

375
00:23:38,350 --> 00:23:40,017
Gaia.

376
00:23:40,018 --> 00:23:42,657
It is the name of Mother Earth.

377
00:23:42,988 --> 00:23:46,757
I feel her. I, I hear her sometimes.

378
00:23:46,758 --> 00:23:49,293
So you're hearing voices in your head?

379
00:23:49,294 --> 00:23:53,230
Voices? No. I hear.

380
00:23:53,231 --> 00:23:55,210
I feel her.

381
00:23:56,935 --> 00:23:59,069
Are you, are you dizzy? Have a seat.

382
00:23:59,070 --> 00:24:01,472
Are- are you lightheaded or- or tired?

383
00:24:01,473 --> 00:24:04,508
Ah, I am always tired these days.

384
00:24:04,509 --> 00:24:06,511
That is nothing new.

385
00:24:07,045 --> 00:24:09,947
But you need answers
to bigger questions than this.

386
00:24:09,948 --> 00:24:11,248
This is true, Al.

387
00:24:11,249 --> 00:24:15,019
The answer is inside you.

388
00:24:15,020 --> 00:24:16,153
What?

389
00:24:16,154 --> 00:24:18,224
What does it mean?

390
00:24:18,657 --> 00:24:20,057
I feel her.

391
00:24:20,058 --> 00:24:23,095
The Earth is tired too, you see.

392
00:24:23,161 --> 00:24:26,130
If we don't give Mother a rest,

393
00:24:26,131 --> 00:24:29,168
then sometimes she can't go on.

394
00:24:30,235 --> 00:24:33,304
Al, could all this
be about your daughter?

395
00:24:33,305 --> 00:24:34,572
That she left?

396
00:24:34,573 --> 00:24:36,373
Oh, no.

397
00:24:36,374 --> 00:24:39,013
Yeah, she needed a rest too.

398
00:24:39,177 --> 00:24:41,156
A rest from me.

399
00:24:41,480 --> 00:24:43,755
We all need a rest.

400
00:24:44,783 --> 00:24:47,126
Don't worry, Dr. Jenna.

401
00:24:47,519 --> 00:24:49,687
Just because someone leaves,

402
00:24:49,688 --> 00:24:52,395
doesn't mean they do not love you.

403
00:24:53,692 --> 00:24:55,227
Hello?

404
00:24:55,627 --> 00:24:57,367
Who's calling?

405
00:25:01,333 --> 00:25:02,666
Hello?

406
00:25:02,667 --> 00:25:04,635
Jenna. It- it's me, Marty.

407
00:25:04,636 --> 00:25:08,049
Oh, hey, Marty. Hold on just a sec.

408
00:25:10,742 --> 00:25:12,142
You okay?

409
00:25:12,143 --> 00:25:13,310
Yep. Hang on.

410
00:25:13,311 --> 00:25:16,413
Just, just trying to get a better signal.

411
00:25:16,414 --> 00:25:17,949
Hold on.

412
00:25:18,683 --> 00:25:21,819
You know what?
I am not okay, by the way.

413
00:25:21,820 --> 00:25:24,455
You just totally blew me off.
My own brother.

414
00:25:24,456 --> 00:25:27,858
Some lame excuse about working late.

415
00:25:27,859 --> 00:25:29,126
Now come on, what's the real story?

416
00:25:29,127 --> 00:25:31,061
You got a hot date?
Who's the lucky girl?

417
00:25:31,062 --> 00:25:32,997
No, no, really. Jenna.

418
00:25:32,998 --> 00:25:34,565
Something kind of serious
popped up in our data.

419
00:25:34,566 --> 00:25:37,201
It's gonna take me some time
to sort it all out.

420
00:25:37,202 --> 00:25:39,739
I just wanted to, um,

421
00:25:40,705 --> 00:25:42,139
uh, so you're okay?

422
00:25:42,140 --> 00:25:43,807
Yeah. I mean, you're just missing dinner.

423
00:25:43,808 --> 00:25:45,676
It's not like it's the end of the world.

424
00:25:45,677 --> 00:25:47,344
Are you okay?

425
00:25:47,345 --> 00:25:48,479
Uh, yeah, yeah.

426
00:25:48,480 --> 00:25:49,780
No, I- I- I'm fine.

427
00:25:49,781 --> 00:25:52,316
Um, but, uh,

428
00:25:52,317 --> 00:25:55,764
is anything out of the ordinary
happening at the clinic?

429
00:25:56,354 --> 00:25:58,390
Yeah. Actually.

430
00:25:58,390 --> 00:26:01,425
About half a dozen people or so
have been coming in all day

431
00:26:01,426 --> 00:26:03,827
complaining of altitude sickness,

432
00:26:03,828 --> 00:26:06,630
like nausea, they're disoriented.

433
00:26:06,631 --> 00:26:09,233
And it doesn't have anything to do
with their cancer treatment.

434
00:26:09,234 --> 00:26:10,668
They're all here for aftercare.

435
00:26:10,669 --> 00:26:13,637
You know, they got through their chemo
and their radiation fine.

436
00:26:13,638 --> 00:26:16,209
So, why are you asking?

437
00:26:18,410 --> 00:26:20,411
Did you read David's book?

438
00:26:20,412 --> 00:26:22,913
I thought you said there was
nothing in there worth reading.

439
00:26:22,914 --> 00:26:25,449
Yeah, I know what I said.
If I could take it back I would.

440
00:26:25,450 --> 00:26:27,918
Uh, I just figured
you might have given it a chance

441
00:26:27,919 --> 00:26:30,456
in spite of your pigheaded brother.

442
00:26:30,755 --> 00:26:32,890
Well, yeah. I did start reading it.

443
00:26:32,891 --> 00:26:34,391
The night of the book signing.

444
00:26:34,392 --> 00:26:36,371
That was a good night.

445
00:26:37,629 --> 00:26:38,963
Yeah, it was.

446
00:26:38,964 --> 00:26:41,665
But, you know,
after you and David had your falling out

447
00:26:41,666 --> 00:26:44,068
and he just disappeared on me,

448
00:26:44,069 --> 00:26:45,769
I wasn't exactly in the,

449
00:26:45,770 --> 00:26:49,506
well, let's curl up with
a really depressing book kind of mood.

450
00:26:49,507 --> 00:26:50,507
You thought it was depressing?

451
00:26:50,508 --> 00:26:52,509
I mean, it was kind of thick
and technical, but--

452
00:26:52,510 --> 00:26:54,011
Hello?

453
00:26:55,180 --> 00:26:57,318
Uh, Jenna?

454
00:26:57,549 --> 00:26:58,993
Marty?

455
00:26:59,718 --> 00:27:01,993
Marty? Ugh.

456
00:27:04,623 --> 00:27:07,626
Hello? Hello?

457
00:27:07,626 --> 00:27:09,393
Hello? Can you hear me now?

458
00:27:09,394 --> 00:27:11,395
Jenna, look,

459
00:27:11,396 --> 00:27:16,266
things are happening that may indicate
an upcoming geophysical event.

460
00:27:16,267 --> 00:27:18,235
In English, please?

461
00:27:18,236 --> 00:27:22,274
Uh, well, I'm, uh,
I'm- I'm still working on the data.

462
00:27:22,307 --> 00:27:25,447
Well, to hell with the data, Marty.
What's going on?

463
00:27:25,477 --> 00:27:27,077
I- I'm not sure yet.

464
00:27:27,078 --> 00:27:28,846
Do you think David may know something?

465
00:27:28,847 --> 00:27:30,648
Well, David has theories and ideas,
Jenna.

466
00:27:30,649 --> 00:27:33,288
I have the facts
right here in front of me.

467
00:27:34,586 --> 00:27:37,788
Marty, clearly,
the two of you need to talk.

468
00:27:37,789 --> 00:27:39,923
I mean, just because he and I
aren't together anymore,

469
00:27:39,924 --> 00:27:42,359
doesn't mean you can't talk.

470
00:27:42,360 --> 00:27:46,569
No. We've gone our separate ways,
in completely opposite directions.

471
00:27:46,865 --> 00:27:48,198
Okay, look. That's silly.

472
00:27:48,199 --> 00:27:51,235
This is important.
Just let him help you with this.

473
00:27:51,236 --> 00:27:52,236
Hello?

474
00:27:52,237 --> 00:27:55,377
Je- hey, Jenna?

475
00:27:55,507 --> 00:27:59,978
Marty? If you can hear me,
gi- just give him another chance.

476
00:28:43,588 --> 00:28:45,255
You're home early.

477
00:28:45,256 --> 00:28:46,690
What happened?

478
00:28:46,691 --> 00:28:48,258
No dessert?

479
00:28:48,259 --> 00:28:50,227
Or dinner for that matter.

480
00:28:50,228 --> 00:28:52,830
It seems that
her mother wasn¡¦t feeling very well.

481
00:28:52,831 --> 00:28:55,140
She was waiting at home for her.

482
00:28:55,767 --> 00:28:59,503
Well, that sounds like a,
a reasonable excuse.

483
00:28:59,504 --> 00:29:01,608
Oh, balls to that.

484
00:29:02,307 --> 00:29:06,643
Can you believe a parent would
live with their child for that long?

485
00:29:06,644 --> 00:29:09,181
Into their 90s?

486
00:29:09,414 --> 00:29:11,985
Oh, Lord, I hope not.

487
00:29:13,551 --> 00:29:15,826
Come on. I've started dinner.

488
00:29:23,461 --> 00:29:26,134
Los Angeles, this is Zero-One, come in.

489
00:29:26,898 --> 00:29:28,706
Something's wrong.

490
00:29:32,237 --> 00:29:33,804
General, we've lost GPS navigation.

491
00:29:33,805 --> 00:29:35,506
We're getting radio interference
out of Edwards.

492
00:29:35,507 --> 00:29:37,748
We're switching to auxiliary com.

493
00:29:37,842 --> 00:29:39,109
Auxiliary?

494
00:29:39,110 --> 00:29:41,879
Microwave when all else fails.

495
00:29:41,880 --> 00:29:43,791
Puts me right at ease.

496
00:29:45,517 --> 00:29:47,351
What's the problem, Pilot?

497
00:29:47,352 --> 00:29:49,126
No problem, General.

498
00:29:52,757 --> 00:29:55,703
Stay with it. Level out.

499
00:29:58,229 --> 00:30:01,403
Panel's down.
We're sitting on visual only.

500
00:30:04,235 --> 00:30:05,969
Well done, Pilot.

501
00:30:05,970 --> 00:30:08,347
Patch me through to Edwards.

502
00:30:09,874 --> 00:30:12,183
Edwards Tower, do you read?

503
00:30:13,444 --> 00:30:17,080
Where are we?
Last coordinates before you lost GPS?

504
00:30:17,081 --> 00:30:18,882
Just over Nevada.

505
00:30:18,883 --> 00:30:21,124
All right, take us down.

506
00:30:21,352 --> 00:30:24,059
This day just keeps getting better.

507
00:30:29,861 --> 00:30:31,328
No more tomatoes?

508
00:30:31,329 --> 00:30:34,198
I shall go into town tomorrow
and pick up some necessities.

509
00:30:34,199 --> 00:30:35,332
What are you talking about?

510
00:30:35,333 --> 00:30:38,669
You- you've just got through
griping about being stood up.

511
00:30:38,670 --> 00:30:41,305
Now you're gonna drive
another 50 miles for her?

512
00:30:41,306 --> 00:30:43,006
What's twisting your britches?

513
00:30:43,007 --> 00:30:45,453
Did you have a wretched afternoon?

514
00:30:45,910 --> 00:30:47,177
Ah, you're right. I'm sorry.

515
00:30:47,178 --> 00:30:49,913
But, uh, it doesn't matter.

516
00:30:49,914 --> 00:30:54,521
I, I suppose there's just some things
you have to accept.

517
00:30:55,320 --> 00:30:57,663
Well, I don't know about accepting.

518
00:30:57,822 --> 00:31:01,860
In my time of life,
you learn to let things slide a little.

519
00:31:02,427 --> 00:31:04,338
Life's too short.

520
00:31:04,896 --> 00:31:08,240
And second chances are priceless.

521
00:31:08,366 --> 00:31:10,901
Dad, don't start with me, all right?

522
00:31:10,902 --> 00:31:12,676
Why not?

523
00:31:13,071 --> 00:31:15,305
You tell me you're fine.

524
00:31:15,306 --> 00:31:19,643
But you won't explain to me
your decidedly melancholic behavior.

525
00:31:19,644 --> 00:31:21,645
I may not be a scientist,

526
00:31:21,646 --> 00:31:24,990
but I'm very much aware of the world
in which we live.

527
00:31:25,083 --> 00:31:28,218
